post_text: Five of our Elysian Fields High School students who are in the firefighter certification program at Kilgore College will be participating in a demonstration on campus Thursday, Sept. 17. The demonstration will involve a LifeFlight helicopter which will land on campus between the tennis courts and football stadium. If the LifeFlight crew is called for an emergency, the LifeFlight demonstration will be rescheduled for a later date. We wanted to make this announcement ahead of time so that everyone will know this is just a demonstration for our students involved in the program. Thank you.

PLEASE SHARE: Elysian Fields ISD offices and campuses will be CLOSED on Thursday, Aug. 27, in advance of possible weather-related complications due to Hurricane Laura which is forecast to pass through the area during the day.

All activities related to EFISD on Thursday are cancelled. This includes both in-person and virtual, online learning and classes as well as extra-curricular activities.

EFISD administration will continue to monitor developments throughout the day on Thursday and make an announcement regarding any possible changes to the Friday schedules as necessary.

Thank you and stay safe, #JacketNation.

post_text: As we come to a close on the first week back in school we want to thank everyone - staff, students, parents, community - for your support and patience. post_text:
Parents, EFISD wishes to any of our parents who would like to serve on this year's Student Healthh Advisory Council (SHAC) committee to please download and complete the form below.

A SHAC (School Health Advisory Council) is a school board-appointed advisory group of individuals who represent different segments of the community. By law, a majority of the members must be persons who are parents of students enrolled in the district and who are not employed by the district. SHACs assist the districts in ensuring that local community values are reflected in health education instruction. Additionally, SHACs can help districts meet performance goals and alleviate financial constraints. SHACs play an important role in strengthening the connection between health and learning. They can help parents and community stakeholders reinforce the knowledge and skills children need to stay healthy for a lifetime.

Contact the district administration office if you would like more information about this opportunity to serve. Thank you.

Please see the schedule below regarding school supply drop-off at the elementary school on Friday, Aug. 7.

One parent and the student will be allowed to enter the school and drop off their supplies. If you cannot make it during the scheduled time below, you may send your child to school with them throughout next week in small, manageable batches.

Parents/guardians of At Home Learners will use the same schedule below to pick up instructional materials they will need also. Please contact the elementary school as soon as possible and let them know if your child will need a device.

Schedule is below:

9:00 - 9:30 A - D
9:45 - 10:15 E - H
10:30 - 11:00 I - L
11:15 - 11:45 M - P
12:00 - 12:30 Q - T
12:45 - 1:15 U-Z

Contact us at 903-633-2465 if you have any questions.

This will be a quick process and we hope to have everyone in and out as quickly as possible. Thank you for your understanding and your support as we work together to get this school year off on the right track next week.

Here are some answers to some of the questions that have been asked here and in general. We want to go ahead and put them here in one post. If your specific questions aren’t answered here please remember to send them to us via e-mail at startstrong@efisd.org.

ELEMENTARY SCHOOL SUPPLY DROPOFF

Parents with multiple children may drop off all school supplies at the same time.

If parents are unable to make their scheduled school supply drop off time, please call the school and speak with the campus principal to make alternate arrangements.

6TH GRADE ORIENTATION

School supplies may be brought during orientation. Please be aware that school lockers will not be in use at this time.

CAR RIDERS

Parents will still need to fill out the car rider form even for riders who will only occasionally be picked up.

We will share more information as it becomes available. Thanks to all for your patience and understanding as we work together during this school year.

Important information of note in response to several questions that have been asked:

*Pre-K and Kindergarten class lists will be made public and posted the week of August 3. Please check the district website next week for that information.

*For Pre-K and Kindergarten Meet the Teacher, only 1 parent and the student may attend. The child is not required to wear a mask, but we ask that siblings not attend.

*We are currently working on the plans for school supply dropoff for Grades 1-5 and will share those as soon as they are finalized.

Thank you all for your patience and understanding as we continue to navigate these waters together. Remember to give us a call at 903-633-2420 or shoot an email to startstrong@efisd.org. We hope to have an FAQ page available on our website soon that will provide answers to some of the main questions we are seeing.

Do your part to help slow the spread of COVID-19.

Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) is a one-time food benefit for families who lost access to free or reduced-price meals due to school closures. Eligible P-EBT families will receive application instructions from schools in late May. The P-EBT application will open the first week of June.

P-EBT food benefits are for children who received SNAP food benefits for March 2020 and children who are certified for free or reduced-price school meals during the 2019-20 Texas school year. For more information, visit: hhs.texas.gov/PEBT

post_text:
#JacketNation, here is another Senior Spotlight! We are sharing stories of our EFHS Class of 2020 to honor our upcoming graduates. Be sure to watch for and to congratulate each one of these outstanding young people.

Senior Spotlight: ISABELLE MESTRES

Favorite EFISD memory: "I don't have a specific memory I favor, but I really like the memories I made in theater."

Greatest accomplishment: "Learning to speak English."

Favorite teacher: ""I don't have a favorite teacher. A lot of my teachers supported me through my high school years, and I am grateful for all of them."

Favorite class: "Theater and Debate. Most of my best memories were made in there."

Activities at EFHS: UIL One-Act Play

After Graduation: Isabelle will be attending the University of Texas at Tyler.

Advice to other students: "You can overcome just about anything if you are persistent and optimistic. Don't give up just because it gets hard."

#ElysianFieldsTX
#TheHive
#ClassOf2020

post_text:
Caden Commander, first grader, had the opportunity for a one-on-one zoom with Dinosaur George, and it made his day! They talked all about ceratopsians and Caden got to ask him a lot of questions, and impressed him with all his knowledge about dinosaurs! Caden got two real dinosaur bones for his birthday--we knew one was a part of a joint from a triceratops but we weren't sure what the other was. Dinosaur George was able to identify that it was a part of a triceratops jaw! Dinosaur George said Caden could trade places with him and teach the class, which really tickled him. 😉 Caden prepped for the zoom by getting all his ceratopsian toys and a few of his fossils all around him to show Dinosaur George.

#JacketNation
#ElysianFieldsTX
#TheHive

post_text:
#JacketNation, here is another Senior Spotlight! We are sharing stories of our EFHS Class of 2020 to honor our upcoming graduates. Be sure to watch for and to congratulate each one of these outstanding young people.

Senior Spotlight: KYLIE HOPKINS

Favorite EFISD memory: "Sitting in the back of the band bus riding to a football game and dancing and listening to music!"

Greatest accomplishment: "Keeping a B in Coach Commanders class!"

Favorite teacher: "Well she’s not a teacher, but Mrs Tina, the nurse. She was always there to encourage me and talk to me when I needed a listening ear!"

Favorite class: "Mrs Woodley’s. We always had fun with whatever she assigned!"

Activities at EFHS: Band

After Graduation: Kylie is headed to Panola College and will later transfer to UT Tyler for their Nursing program.

Advice to other students: "Enjoy it and don’t rush it! It goes by fast enough already!"

#ElysianFieldsTX
#TheHive
#ClassOf2020

KGAS radio station in Carthage will be running salutes to the Class of 2020 in all our area high schools! Parents, grandparents, and friends may salute their special senior and tell about them in a 30-second commercial. Participants may call in and voice it themselves or write up what they would like to say and KGAS will voice.

Cost is $49 for the commercial and it will run until their date of graduation with approximately 25 commercials.

If interested, call KGAS at 903-693-7176 and ask for Judy.

Thanks you for your support of the Class of 2020!

post_text:
Dear EFISD Parents and Students,

This week parents and students will be able to clean out desks and lockers to get their personal items.

We ask that everyone please abide by the following rules:

1. Follow the schedule provided. If someone is near the locker or desk that you need to clean please wait until they are finished. Please stay at least six feet away from other people.

2. Please make sure the locker is empty of everything. Trash cans will be in the hallways for any unwanted items. Bolt cutters are available if you need the lock cut off.

3. We recommend that you wear a mask and gloves. This is only a recommendation and NOT mandatory.

Thank you #JacketNation.

Favorite class: Coach Pruitt's class. "You never knew what was going to happen in his class. Every day, it was something new."

Activities at EFHS: Baseball and one year of football.

After Graduation: Kevn plans to attend TSTC to become a lineman.

Advice to other students: "Act like every day is your last day of high school. Don't take it for granted. It flies by, just have fun and be yourself."

post_text:
A message of encouragement from Mrs. Struwe to her students:

"To say that we as teachers miss our students would be an understatement. I hope that you and your families have taken advantage of all the extra time and opportunities you have had to spend time with your families and do things you may not normally find yourself doing. I want to say thank you to all the parents who have stepped up to help their children continue their education outside the school house. It has been quite an experience for all of us to work together to ensure our children do not fall behind and stay prepared for the following school year. I really hope and pray that you all are getting to spend as much quality time with your family as much as I am mine. I still can't wait to see you all real soon!"

#JacketNation
#ElysianFieldsTX

Favorite EFISD memory: "Pulling the shower from the old lab and almost flooding the room."

After Graduation: Britney will attend Northwestern State University and to major in Biology and minor in Veterinary Technology.

#JacketNation, here is another Senior Spotlight! We are sharing stories of our EFHS Class of 2020 to honor our upcoming graduates. Be sure to watch for and to congratulate each one of these outstanding young people.

Senior Spotlight: DAET TAPIA

Favorite EFISD memory: "My favorite memory is my first Cross Country district championship my first year."

Greatest accomplishment: "Winning district in Cross Country and qualifying for Regionals by myself."

Favorite teacher: Mrs. Sims, because "she took over from Coach D and always pushed me and motivated me to not only be the best student-athlete but to be the best person I could be in life."

Favorite class: "My favorite class is Art. It is a fun,creative class where there is no wrong in what you do."

Activities at EFHS: Cross Country, Track

After Graduation: Daet plans to attend Panola College, then transfer to a four-year university to major in Sports Media.

Advice to other students: "Never slip up and get discouraged for one bad season. Keep working hard and everything will pay off."

#ElysianFieldsTX
#TheHive
#ClassOf2020

#JacketNation, here is another Senior Spotlight! We will be sharing stories of our EFHS Class of 2020 each day to honor our upcoming graduates. Be sure to watch for and to congratulate each one of these outstanding young people.

Senior Spotlight: ADRIAN PACHECO

Favorite EFISD memory: "All the home football games."

Greatest accomplishment: "Going to the second round of the playoffs in basketball last year."

Favorite teachers: Mrs. White, "because she's funny and easy to get along with."

Favorite class: Mrs. Langley's BIMS class, "because I like computer work."

Activities at EFHS: Fellowship of Christian Athletes, UIL Academics, National Honor Society, Student Council, Volleyball, Basketball, Softball.

After Graduation: Adrian plans to attend Southern Arkansas University to complete a degree in Nursing.

Advice to other students: "Don't take these years for granted, they go by faster than you can imagine!"

#ElysianFieldsTX
#TheHive
#ClassOf2020

Hello #JacketNation! We want to recognize and applaud our students who are continuing to work hard and show tremendous discipline and tenacity during this home learning time brought about by school closure. Each week here on our Facebook page, we will recognize students in every grade level as "At-Home Learning Heroes" for their effort, motivation and completion of at-home learning assignments. Join us as we celebrate our students for staying true to our #JacketPride and their hard work!

AT-HOME LEARNING HEROES - EFISD 1st Grade

ANNABELLE GRIFFIN
From communications with her parents and pictures submitted, it is obvious that Annabelle is excelling at remote learning. She is enjoying completing her assignments and stays busy. Way to go Annabelle!

post_text:
#JacketNation, here is our first Senior Spotlight! We will be sharing stories of our EFHS Class of 2020 each day to honor our upcoming graduates. Be sure to watch for and to congratulate each one of these outstanding young people.

Senior Spotlight: HAILEY ALANIZ

Favorite EFISD memory: Adrian falling during a softball game and saying "oof."

Greatest accomplishment: My many close friends

Favorite teachers: The Hurtas - because they treat me as their own kiddo. They call me "HayHay" and that honestly makes me happy.

Favorite class: Forensic Science, because "Coach Hurta would make up last-minute labs and they'd end up being fun.

Activities at EFHS: National Honor Society, Varsity Softball, Varsity Tennis, Yearbook Staff, Future Farmers of America, Class Parliamentarian.

After Graduation: Hailey will join the United States Air Force, with plans to study Radiology after her time in the service.

Advice to other students: "Live in the moment, don’t dwell on the past."

#ElysianFieldsTX
#TheHive

From Elisia Ingram:

Piper is finishing up her Pre-Cal for the day, and Denny is working on his Honors Algebra. Piper finishing up her Pre-Cal for the day. I’ve also had them both helping cook. It’s a great way to learn everyday math and measurements. Also, we are planning menus using ingredients already on hand and helping with laundry and other assorted chores that we would normally leave for the housekeeper.

Oh! And we are also planning and planting garden spots too! We havee been researching what plants grow well with others, which like sun or shade, and the best spots in the yard to plant.

post_text:
Vibes From The Hive:

Hi everyone!!!

I hope and pray that you all are well and enjoying the time we have been given to spend with our families. I’ve loved seeing everyone’s posts on Facebook and all the different ways our students continue to learn and grow. The smiles and joy on their sweet faces makes my heart happy.
Our wonderful parents are doing an awesome job of working with their kids! So many are helping with the homework packets and then extending the learning into every day lessons. There are so many precious memories being made during this time! Our fabulous teachers have gone above and beyond what we have asked them to do. They are true superheroes! I cannot be any prouder of them! Sometimes we go through situations and we can’t understand why until after we are clear and able to look back. I believe God has a reason for this and one day we will be able to look back and say “Thank you, God.” Until then, just know that I love you all and miss you SO much!!

Debra Kassaw, Elementary Assistant Principal

#JacketNation
#ElysianFieldsTX
#TheHive

post_text:
#JacketNation: This afternoon, Texas Gov. Greg Abbott announced that all schools in Texas will remain closed until May 4, 2020.

Due to this order from the governor, Elysian Fields ISD will be closed until that time. Our teachers and staff will continue to provide online learning activities and assignments for our students.

Thank you so much for your support and patience during this time as we work together to educate our children during this time. Stay safe, stay well, and continue to follow us as we work through this time together.

#ElysianFieldsTX
#TheHive

post_text:
Vibes From The Hive:

Students,

I miss seeing you... honest! Be sure that you are reading your emails & checking EF notifications. Please take the time to do all of your class assignments/requirements because they are important. We have an amazing district that always has your best interest in mind.

Take some time to do something special for someone else, you may have to think outside the box. Be innovative. It might be something as simple as unloading the dishwasher or mowing the lawn without being told to do so or checking in with an elderly grandparent or neighbor to see if they need anything.

Keep in mind, this time of restrictive isolation is affecting everyone & it is new & unknown. Be kind, helpful, & understanding to & of others.
Always remember that you are smart, make good decisions.

Take Care,

Shannon Earl, EF High School Teacher

#JacketNation
#ElysianFieldsTX

post_text:
Vibes From The Hive...words of encouragement from our teachers and staff in EFISD during this time of school closure:

Today was Jean Day! Well, really every day is Jean Day (if not PJ day). Usually Jean Days are a teacher's favorite day, but not now. Without seeing my students' wonderful faces how could it be?

I miss each and everyone of my kiddos so much. I miss our discussions and your inquisitive nature, but most of all your wonderful dance moves when we had our celebration of knowledge. I hope to see these all very soon, but until then please keep in touch through Google Classroom or emails.

I hope you have the time to check out photosynthesis in action, especially on these beautiful spring days. Lastly, I would like to leave you a challenge. If you figure out the answer email me the answer to get extra bonus points. What kind of dog does a science teacher have?

Miss you guys and gals,

Mrs. O'Brien - EFMS 7th Grade Teacher

#JacketNation
#ElysianFieldsTX

post_text:
Vibes From The Hive...words of encouragement from our teachers and staff in EFISD during this time of school closure. Stay safe and strong, #JacketNation!

Dear Students,

Do you remember when Mr. Buddy Ritter visited our district earlier this year? I do! When he came, he shared with us his incredible life story. It was filled with determination and one powerful word. HOPE!

Despite how things are, I encourage you to keep believing and to know you are loved. You have touched the lives of your teachers and make them who they are. Since school has been closed, they have been lost and that is because they do not have you. They miss your laughter, smiles, and antics.

They cannot wait to be reunited with you and neither can I. You make us all complete and happy.

While you are at home though, have as much fun as you possibly can. Sing, dance, be silly, paint, draw, laugh out loud, and most importantly be a kid.

Love always,
Monica Simmons, EFISD Curriculum Director

#ElysianFieldsTX
#TheHive

post_text:
Students in Jody Morgan's 7th Grade Writing class at Elysian Fields Middle School have been busy with new ways of learning while school has been closed.

Brody - "I’m doing some wood burning and making signs for my family. I’m going to stain and put polyurethane on them too. I’ve been fishing some and riding my 4-wheeler."

Addy - "Aside from using my mom’s Facebook, I’m working on this 1,000 piece puzzle while quarantined. I’d rather be reading, too!"

Shelby - "I have been learning to take care of baby ducks. We have five babies that are two weeks old. I have to clean their cage every morning, feed and water them."

#JacketNation

"Keep your face to the sunshine, and you cannot see a shadow." - Helen Keller

Our Elysian Fields ISD Superintendent, Mr. Maynard Chapman, recently recognized Elizabeth Wheeler for her exceptional service to the district. Mrs. Wheeler performed an act of heroism by which she demonstrated a great degree of selflessness, personal courage, and devotion to duty.

We would like to also wish Mrs. Wheeler and her family all the best in the future, as they are leaving us with her husband having taken a position in another district. Thank you for all you’ve done for our students and we wish you guys all the best!

Martha Lovaasen is also pictured with Mr. Chapman and Mrs. Wheeler. We appreciate all that you do for our students!

post_text:
Students in Lexi Commander's Pre-Calculus and Calculus classes recently enjoyed a sweet treat.

They celebrated Pi Day, which is celebrated on March 14 around the world. Pi (Greek letter “π”) is the symbol used in mathematics to represent a constant — the ratio of the circumference of a circle to its diameter — which is approximately 3.14159.

Pi Day is an annual opportunity for math enthusiasts to recite the infinite digits of Pi, talk to their friends about math, and to eat pie.

Instead of eating pie, the students ate cookie cakes baked by Jessica Guilhas and Lena Brunner.

What a fun and "sweet" learning experience for our students!

#JacketNation

Our students in Leadership & Tech took on an assignment in which they had to "invent" a new product. The students had to make a scale, commercial, jingle and a magazine advertisement. Students created the following products: body odor machine; a dress code patch to cover holes; a pencil that you speak into and writes notes; a medical watch (blood pressure, asthma); a phone accessory that projects images off your phone; and a hat that can change your phone. Our students are so creative!

With the help of Mr. And Mrs. Brad Sims, we are bringing "Girls On The Run" to Elysian Fields! This is a non-competitive, 10-week life skills and running program intended to empower our young girls in grades 3-5.

Please share this application link (rmd.me/KpnIZhDDms9) with other families, as we can accept a total of 15 girls. It is strictly on a first- come, first-serve basis.

Financial aid is available, and training days will be arranged around the track schedule. We will begin the week of March 9.

post_text:
The Elysian Fields Elementary PTO is trying something different this year for our Spring Fundraiser. In fact, we're calling it our "No Sales Fundraiser!" This will help us cover the cost of Spring expenses.

We are still raising funds for playground equipment, end-of-year playday, Teacher Appreciation Week, and the Awards Assembly. However, all we ask is that you pledge to give a donation in your child's name.

Your time and efforts are always appreciated, and your child will be rewarded for your contribution. The grade that raised the most money during the "No Sales Fundraiser" will receive a pizza party!

Rewards for pledge amounts are:

$10 in pledges -- Free Dairy Queen Ice Cream
$50 in pledges -- 1 Movie Ticket
$100 in pledges -- Get your Principals and Officer with silly string!
$200 in pledges -- Participation in the "Game on Game" Truck!

Students will receive each item as they level up in pledges.

As always, thank you for supporting EF Elementary! Contact the school if you have questions!

post_text: Monday, Mrs. King provided the Culinary Arts students with a tour of the school kitchen, introduced them to the cafeteria staff, and explained the Nutrition Standards in the National School Lunch Program (NSLP). After a bit of teaching, the students were encouraged to create their own menu for a day and present it to the class. She did a wonderful job explaining the rules and nutrition requirements (sodium, saturated fat, and caloric guidelines) that are mandated by the USDA, TDA, and Health Inspector. She also explained the cafeteria's budgetary needs to include staffing requirements along with raw materials. It was a wonderful day of learning! Thank you Mrs. King for your heart of service towards our students, and your willingness to share so generously your time and expertise! Students left the classroom knowing that Mrs. King valued their input and ideas, and that she would seriously try to implement their ideas into the menu.

Elysian Fields ISD wishes to express a huge Thank You to our EF Community and faculty for your support of our students, Brooklyn Simmons and Louis Martinez and they families. Louis is a high school student and Brooklyn is in the second grade, and EFISD sold shirts for both families to receive a portion of the proceeds to help with medical expenses. The outpouring of love for these two families has been overwhelming and appreciated. Louis is currently at Dallas Children's Hospital and Brooklyn will also be there over Thanksgiving Break.

Thank you EF and the Yellowjacket Family!

On Thursday, November 14, the Elysian Fields 7th Grade Leadership and Technology students visited KSLA Channel 12 News. They met Adraia Goins and watched a live taping of the twelve o'clock news. The Leadership and Technology students have their own newscast called "Live From the Hive" and can be viewed on Youtube. They interview Middle School students and teachers and ask the tough questions all students want to know.

Pictured are: Luis Perez, Athan Walton, Allison O'Brien, Layton Derouen, Adria Goins, Lawson Swank, James Ware, Stetson Swilley, Jonah Hurta, Shelby Roberts, Collin Caudle, Brianna Perez, and Gracey Struwe. The leadership and technology teacher is Crystal O'Brien.

We like to send a special thank you to the KSLA news crew and Adria Goins for your hospitality and providing this valuable learning experience for our students!

post_text:
On November 4, three of Elysian Fields' senior students were honored as Elks Lodge Students of the Month for the first quarter.

Mary Grace Roos was the Student of the Month for August, Justice Gooch for September, and Tyler Choi for November.

This is an honor awarded seniors in eight of our area school districts. Students are honored quarterly at the Elks Lodge in Marshall, and are accompanied by their families. Each student chooses an adult, such as a teacher, counselor, coach, or principal, to speak on their behalf about their accomplishments and reason for selection.

Being selected as an Elks Lodge Student of the Month makes these students eligible for the many scholarships made available nationally by the Elks organization.

Thank you Elks Lodge for honoring our students, and congratulations to these fine young people!
